@startuml paak_auth_to_child_lock_signal_flow
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true

title PAAK Auth To Child Lock Signal Flow\n(PAAK/drive context -> BCM -> door child-lock enforcement)

participant "PAAK / drive context" as AccessCtx #F4F7FB
participant "BCM\nbody access owner" as BCM #E8F7E8
participant "Rear door ECUs" as RearDoors #FFF4CC
participant "Observers / panels" as Obs #E8F0FE

== Access / Drive Inputs ==

AccessCtx -> BCM : gPaakAuthLevel\ngPaakProximityState\ngPaakState\ngDriveState
BCM -> BCM : evaluate door access and drive-state safety
BCM -> BCM : childLockState =\n(manualMode == 0 and driveState > 0) ? 1 : 0
note right of BCM
Representative gating inputs
- paakAuthLevel / proximity / state
- driveState
- manualMode
end note

== Child Lock Publish ==

BCM -> RearDoors : frmDoorControlMsg\nChildLockCmd
BCM -> BCM : mDoorState.ChildLockState\nfor body state publish
note right of BCM
Representative outputs
- ChildLockCmd
- ChildLockState
end note

== Door Enforcement ==

RearDoors -> RearDoors : childLockActive blocks rear-door unlock/open
RearDoors -> Obs : rear door status /\nchild-lock visibility

note over AccessCtx, Obs
Representative runtime chain
1. Access and drive context reach BCM
2. BCM decides whether child lock must be active
3. BCM publishes ChildLockCmd on the door-control path
4. Rear door ECUs enforce the lock and observers show the protected state
end note

@enduml
